Alright, I figured it out.

Because you are not allowed to cast from a base class back to a derived class, the functions which return a new instance must be called as base constructors from derived constructors.

To simplify things I made a single constructor in the base class which returns a modified instance.

In the derived classes, I implement a single private constructor that takes a list of changes to make. This has the advantage that it&#39;s pretty much boilerplate.

Then each derived class is able to call a constructor of its own type, which then passes the work to the base class constructor. This avoids the casting issues I was running into.

As an example (rough pseudocode ahead)

    public abstract class BaseClass {
      protected BaseClass(BaseClass Source, var changes...) ...
    }
    
    public class DerivedClass {
      private DerivedClass(DerivedClass Source, var changes)
        : BaseClass(Source, changes) { }
    
    public DerivedClass MakeChange(var change) {
      ...set up changed values...
      return new DerivedClass(this, changes)
      }
    }

