Lets take the template function you have

    template&lt; typename Tp&gt; Tp makeObj()
    {
        /// How is this allocated
        Tp obj;
        obj-&gt;data = 10;
        return obj;
    }

and expand it with the type

    MyClass* makeObj()
    {
        /// How is this allocated
        MyClass* obj;
        obj-&gt;data = 10;
        return obj;
    }

Now you can clearly see that you don&#39;t actually allocate a `MyClass` object, only a *pointer* to it. This pointer will be uninitialized and dereferencing it will lead to *undefined behavior*.

One possible solution is to not have a template argument being a pointer, but the type, then explicitly use a pointer to it in the function template:

    // Declare the return-type to be a pointer
    //                       v
    template&lt; typename Tp&gt; Tp* makeObj()
    {
        /// How is this allocated
        Tp* obj = new Tp;  // Declare variable as a pointer,
                           // and actually create an instance of the type
        obj-&gt;data = 10;
        return obj;
    }

Use it as

    // Explicitly declares as a pointer
    //      v
    MyClass *tmp = makeObj&lt;MyClass&gt;();
    //                     ^^^^^^^
    // And pass the plain class-type as the template argument, not a pointer

It&#39;s really simple: the way you use it, `Tp` is treated as a value. It doesn&#39;t matter that it may be a pointer, since pointers are values. You could think of a pointer as `intptr_t` with some extras added. So, `makeObj` makes an instance of *the pointer*. But this pointer doesn&#39;t point to anything. So, `obj-&gt;data = 10` is undefined behavior. And from this point onwards, your code can be doing anything. That&#39;s where the analysis ends. You need to fix `makeObj`. I presume that `makeObj` is supposed to be a factory function.

Below is an example of how `makeObj` could look. You really don&#39;t want to be messing about with raw pointers. Factory functions should return `std::unique_ptr` or an equivalent (e.g. `kj::Own` from [capnproto][capnp]). That&#39;s how idiomatic modern C++ should look.

You also don&#39;t need to use console i/o to confirm that things work as expected: you can `assert`, and the debugger will stop at the point where the assertion fails. There&#39;s a small step from that to test-driven development; you&#39;d use a variant of &quot;assert&quot; that&#39;s specific to the test framework you&#39;re using. But even without a test framework, it&#39;s easy to check things using assert when you&#39;re playing with stuff.

Given that we live in the wonderful times where you can access a C++ compiler and debugger in the browser, you can experiment with the code below at https://onlinegdb.com/BJZOB6gKH

```
#include &lt;cassert&gt;
#include &lt;memory&gt;

template &lt;class T, class... Args&gt; std::unique_ptr&lt;T&gt; makeObj(Args &amp;&amp;... args) {
  auto ptr = std::make_unique&lt;T&gt;(std::forward&lt;Args&gt;(args)...);
  ptr-&gt;data = 10;
  return ptr;
}

struct MyType { 
    int foo = {};
    int data = {};
    MyType() = default;
    MyType(int foo, int data) : foo(foo), data(data) {}
};

int main()
{
    auto t = makeObj&lt;MyType&gt;(5, 20);
    assert(t-&gt;foo == 5);
    assert(t-&gt;data == 10);
    auto u = makeObj&lt;MyType&gt;();
    assert(u-&gt;foo == 0);
    assert(u-&gt;data == 10);
}
```

